South Africa and Indonesia agreed to strengthen cooperation in business, trade and investment.These will be guided by the Plan of Action 2017-2021 document, which will drive bilateral relations forward. We have urged our ministers to drive the processes in taking our relationship to the next level, President Jacob Zuma said.He was speaking to the media after bilateral talks with his Indonesian counterpart President Joko Widodo.Zuma, who is in Jakarta for a state visit, also attended the 2017 Indian Ocean Rim Association (Iora) summit there. We have also agreed to work together to realise the aspirations of the countries of the Iora, Zuma said.On the multilateral front, the two sides agreed especially to consult and cooperate in the UN and other global formations they both belong to. This will ensure that we continue to work towards a more democratic and equitable global governance system, Zuma said.TNA REPORTERnews@thenewage.co.za